MEMORY HIERARCHY:is the organization of different types of memory in a structure that allows for efficient data storage and retrieval. The hierarchy is designed to balance speed, size, and cost, ensuring that the system can process data efficiently while keeping costs manageabl.
ADDRESSING MODES IN MEMORY MANAGEMENT:is 
the different ways in which the operands (data or addresses) for an instruction can be specified. They define how the CPU can access data in memory or registers, determining how memory locations are calculated and how operands are retrieved or manipulated during execution. Addressing modes provide flexibility and efficiency in program execution. 







